IBM history: From cheese cutting to global flights
The company IBM (International Business Machines), founded in New York a hundred years ago, initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
She took the name IBM only in 1924 - originally it was a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The founding stone to the later company IBM was the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 1980s of the 19th century.
They possessed technologies such as the famous card watches to register the beginning and end of work.
Charles Ranlett Flint became the architect of this new company, who was also chairman of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the competition company Thomas J. Watson to help him manage the company.
This Leader then even put the founders of IBM in the shadows - based on Watson's ideas to date is the invincible culture and identity of the company.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name betrays, began with the manufacture and distribution of all kinds of machines for trade - from sausage and cheese cutting to cash.
In the first four decades Watson led the company, he doubled its sales to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable for the company that he was in the chair for the whole forty years, only then he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, engineers and computers from IBM helped to lead flights to space - to Merkur and Saturn and in 1969 also the famous flight of man to the moon.
In 1964 IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the IBM System / 360 series.
A classic PC that set the computer standard of that time came to the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand it purchased the consultant part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus fully entered the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
