Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorised state travel agencies in ČSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies only sold journeys to the socialist East Block countries at the time, and in the West only selected.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Black Sea Peninsula), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A minor exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one could also travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that it was not even allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries by citizens of the East Block (i.e. the Czechoslovakia).
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual trips were not possible.
Even then the travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but then one had to buy huge snakes or stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
This was not the case for a long time.
The so-called foreign exchange usage - the condition for an exit to the West - was granted only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovakian currency was not a free exchange currency, so it would have been impossible to raise the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The white majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dicks - a habit that lasts until today.
The total revolution of 1989 followed a journey revolution of the Czechs on foot.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things, the Czech Republic spent 4.5 million of its foreign holidays last year in countries around the world.
A tremendous paradox, which is no longer known today, is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
From the beginning of the 90s of the last century, foreign exchange obligations in neighbouring Western European countries were abolished, leading to a huge wave of short visits mainly to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovakians simply couldn't get enough for a long time from their trips to the West, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
So the Czech holidaymen slept on traveling to Paris in the tent in the park, because who had already had the money for accommodation at the hotel or in a pension at that time.
A typical feature of foreign travel from Czechs was a trunk with preserves, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the free exchange of Czech crown - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the western currency freely.
Our level of life and thus also the average salaries increased, which led to another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased travel demand, travel agencies began to prepare regular travel by charter flights after 1997, making flight trips unbelievable compared to the past thanks to the possibility of negotiating quantity discounts.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, already had a currency-free payment transaction with all the highly developed countries in the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-gathering" travel came in 2000, when the first direct charter flight to an exotic country - to Thailand, thanks to the high demand.
Since then, direct charter planes with Czech passengers have been flying to far away sunny countries every year; this year you fly 12 exotic destinations directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 Tsd. Czechs travel every year to exotic countries!
Another important moment in the epoch, which characterised our "post-revolutionary" development, came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the US suspended the visa requirement for Czech tourists, which definitely included our country among the highly developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent for the first time more than half their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than 15 Tsd per head for a single vacation stay including the cost of holidays.
