Climate discrepancies slow down the economy
In the first year where Mario López Valdez is at the government, unemployment and black work increased in Sinaloa, while foreign investments decreased and the economy stagnated.
In 2011, Sinaloas will be remembered in economic history. It is the first year in which Mario López Valdez, who referred to himself as the initiator of change and had great hopes of economic growth, is at the government. However, due to the climate aberrations, growth cannot be mentioned, but on the contrary, the main economic indicators deteriorated.
The low temperatures in February caused not only millions of losses in agriculture, but also narrow limits to the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity by 3.6 per cent in the first quarter. This is mainly due to the historical decline in agricultural development by 31.16 per cent, which has reversed further economic sectors.
According to a report published by Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (i.e. the Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development) on the effects of the frost, 582 000 hectares of agricultural land used were damaged, 78.03 percent of which were wholly destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent were partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity by November continued to increase unemployment in the Mexican state. The Institute Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid rise in unemployment in the first quarter of the year, since from January to March 55 053 inhabitants of Sinaloa did not have employment, which corresponds to 4.53 per cent of the labour force. In the second quarter the unemployment rate increased to 5.28 per cent and from July to September to 6.19 per cent, resulting in 74 000 unemployed in Sinaloa, which is 18 969 more people than in the first quarter of the year.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa in the year is due to several factors. Economic scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), commented that public institutions' policy indirectly explains the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently observing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors. Among other things, liquidity losses in the market due to the reduction of funds by the legislation adopted to combat money laundering in the Congress, because for those who raise bans, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them or use them for anything else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment also occupies a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the country in search of work abroad, especially in the United States, has fallen, on the one hand due to the problems of entry and on the other hand because it is difficult to find work there too. These people stay here and look for work, which causes unemployment to rise," he says.
Black work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious when taking into account the high proportion of black work, which, according to INEGI, comprises 60.38 per cent of those employed in the country who work without paying in the social security funds.
Unemployment and black work are the lowest wages in Mexico, according to the statistics of the Institute of Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Insurance Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government Agency for Labour and Social Services in Mexico).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos until September, which is much less than the general government average, which is 7375 pesos.
Reduction of ADI
In addition to the reduction of economic activity and the rising unemployment, the largest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) over the last ten years is recorded in 2011. According to Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI was 630 597 dollars from January to June, which corresponds to a swing of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 143 312 dollars in the same period of the previous year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (government authority for economic development), on its side, recorded a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies from the tertiary sector.
The debt
In the light of the economic crisis, the national government requested a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos at the National Congress in July to be invested in the reactivation of the economy in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities.
Responses
For the representatives of entrepreneurship, the first year of the government made Mario López Valdé's government inability apparent.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of Manufacturing Industry in Mexico), said that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonise the views of the different sectors, including the national government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really very poor this year. It needs to be worked hard to recover the land lost this year and in 2012 we have to make a double effort. The efforts of all and especially the progress of the already well-coordinated government team have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slowly economic development
Loredo López said that events such as the Frost at the beginning of the year made the economic development of the country difficult and slower.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including frost. One of the most important effects is a slow economy that is not sufficiently moving to create an economic dynamism that could create an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. That is why we will end the year far below our expectations," he said.
Redefine vocation
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Mexican Entrepreneurship Association) in Sinaloa, stated that it was necessary to encourage the state to more dynamic productive activities.
"Generally we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme to redefine the country's economic profession and line, because it is important to activate all material and human resources Sinaloas," he said.
There's a lot to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that will guide the government's efforts in a better direction.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power has made progress with the government.
"There are areas in which one can say that the government has acted more extensively. What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
