Asphalt from UNAM prevents stroke holes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University UNAM develops modified asphalt with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs were taken into account from the street siege, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200 000 stroke holes if the rainy time at the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city area of the valley of Mexico) broke out, Rafael Herrera Nájera, researchers at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM, warned and assured that if the layout and maintenance of the ashtray were done adequately, the number of slaughters was significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Blowlights from a technical perspective," he held at the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible developed with polymers modified asphalt to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, but that has greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believed that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climate, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of the road siege and thus avoid the occurrence of strokes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heavier part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound, some of which have a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalt - and the other part a low - the so-called malthene. Together, they grant the street coating its characteristic delicate behavior.
The adhesive behaviour of the asphalt means that it acts like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180 ° C, it is very liquid at 120 ° C and almost solid at 50 ° C while it becomes fragile at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of asphalt on the streets is not identical, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemistry engineer performed.
The researcher of the FQ noticed that the streets of Mexico city had a majority of flexible road coating, consisting of six material layers, of which the last three were asphalt.
Between the top layers there is a wear layer of asphalt, which consists of small, in asphalt bathed and then attached stones.
Every single stone of this wear layer had been bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of power in the road coating.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better," the chemistry engineer said.
"Over the wear layer," he said, "one last layer is interpreted, the so-called carriage layer consisting of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since these layers are in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they need to produce friction.
The most forces received and distributed by this road layer also require an appropriate thickness and the material it consists of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially moisture and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to take into account, above all the water, "he said," because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the site gets wet, water penetrates the layer and comes out only difficult again. This causes a deviation of all layers of the road surface and consequently the occurrence of stroke holes.
When a stroke hole arises, "he said," first the cover layer is carried off, while the wear layer is not affected until after that. But the damage is not caused immediately, but it is a process that should be maintained with the first signs through appropriate maintenance programmes. "
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (Mexican National Research System) stated that the vehicle load is another important cause for the occurrence of stroke lamps. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of road belag must always be in proportion to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this rule is complied with in order to avoid frequent stroke lamps.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that a lot of research was still waiting for, for example, on asbestos mutations that were already on the market in other countries and with which the battleholes could be repaired easily and without the use of high temperatures.
