North Stream, new gate to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the Baltic Sea sea base and connects Western Europe directly to Russia, was put into operation.
It is intended to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to commit this event with Gloria and Gloria.
More than 500 invited guests, including four Heads of State and Government, attended last Tuesday at the Baltic Sea coast under orchestra cooling and at the finely decorated buffet of the inauguration of the new North Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly under sea level.
The German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medwedew, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his colleague Mark Rutte from the Netherlands have symbolically turned together the control of the valve which transports Russian gas into the Western European network.
The new gas pipeline is intended to supply 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gases per year through a first pipeline of 1.224 km length that connects the Sankt Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern to Western Europe.
A second pipeline that allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic meters of gas - equivalent of total French consumption - will be completed at the end of 2012.
And you already make the possibility of building a third line sound on your own route.
For Gazprom, the timely and punctual completion of this enormous construction seems to be a victory.
The project was strongly disputed in Poland and the Baltic States.
In fact, the North Stream pipeline will allow direct gas supply to Germany, while avoiding any trace through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) on land roads.
That is why these two countries are losing a little their power: for them it is now more difficult to put pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, who was most involved in the debate, was not relieved to compare the North Stream pipeline with a "new German-Soviet pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply through the support of this Russian project.
This, however, is at the expense of the dismantling of European energy, as the project has broken between Western and Eastern Europeans.
Russia has completed its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, western countries that have strong gas consumption and whose gas reserves are inclined to be achieved in just five years.
