All this explains the broad smile of the many Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin regarding gas supply.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an excellent technique.
The underwater pipeline consists of steel with concrete numbers to protect it from ship's anchorages.
It rests on the sea floor at about 200 m depth.
During their construction, minefields dating from the Second World War had to be removed.
"About a hundred mines had to be carefully removed or destroyed," said Jens Müller, spokesman of the North Stream Society.
In addition, reinforced measures had to be taken to protect fauna and flora.
The line is a long snake of metal, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which has been interrupted throughout the length by nothing: neither by valves nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers have withdrawn from it as Sweden was little interested in seeing a Russian state company permanently at the level of its coasts.
"In case of a hazard, we close the gas flow in less than one minute," Jens Müller specified.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the gas pipeline thus evaporates into the air.
However, this case is considered to be very unlikely by the designers, since the welding seams were estimated to be resistant by one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured both by a underwater robot controlled for external observation purposes from a sea ship and by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the form of a cigar, measures a meter diameter, is introduced into the inner pipe line and is moved through the gas pressure.
After three full days of movement through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information about any deformations of the metal at its arrival.
The gas pipeline was designed to work for fifty years without even having to undergo the smallest repair.
The gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entrance point, 100 bar at the exit site.
Five companies have united their forces to achieve this project.
